flowRoot.flowPara: +++ An addictive incremental game about particle physics research +++
Run your own laboratory, collect data, hire physicists, and make historic discoveries!

The game aims to be fun and educational at the same time. Using the very addictive game loop of typical idle games, it binds the player for an extended amount of time. Physics content is introduced through a reward system.
While progressing, you have access to descriptions about important particle physics discoveries and get insights into the scientific research process in a fun and accessible way.
The main target audience are high school students, although the game can be played by anyone who wants to learn something about physics or just to have fun!

The CERN Summer Student Webfest is an annual hackathon at CERN, the European Organization for Nuclear Research. Participants work on interesting new ideas over the course of a weekend and create web applications that encourage the public to learn more about science and in particular about CERN, the LHC, and physics. Students also explore humanitarian projects that involve web-based solutions, together with CERN’s partner UNOSAT.

Particle Clicker is a completely web-based, client-side game. Written from scratch in HTML5 and JavaScript using modern technologies, it is playable in any browser. A Responsive interface is displayed with the help of jQuery, Angular JS, and Bootstrap, so it looks nice on all of your devices, desktop or mobile.
Data is necessary for research. Only with data can you make discoveries. You can collect data by clicking on your detector. Once you hire students, they will also collect data for you.
In Particle Clicker, you can research many interesting particles.
Every time your lab researches something, it becomes more popular. This "reputation" guarantees you a contant stream of funding in form of "jetons" (JTN), the coins used for buying coffee at CERN.

PhD students, Postdocs, Professors and many more are the types of workers you can hire in Particle Clicker to make your academic life easier. They will ease the tedious task of collecting data for you so you can focus on your research.

The game presents an oversimplification of particle physics research. The basic game loop represents the fundamental process of collecting data, making discoveries, receiving grant money, and hiring people to do more research.

In reality, much like in the game, more and more data is needed for more complex discoveries. The game takes you on a historic journey from the discovery of CP violation in 1964 to recent discoveries like the Higgs boson or the Ξb- baryon.

You can also use your funding to improve the performance of your workers and your detector. Hardware upgrades like increased luminosity give more data per click and improved quality of life through - for example - free coffee makes your workers more productive.
Since its release in August 2014, Particle Clicker has been played by 140'000 people from over 150 different countries. It was featured at Mozilla Festival 2014 in London.

Cory Doctorow from boingboing.net called it a "meth-addictive supercollider sim" and countless people have shared their love for the game on Twitter, Facebook, Reddit and many other places on the internet. Camille Gévaudan from the French magazine Libération gave it the attribute "Classe".
